8 // ----
9 // This file defines the pass which converts floating point instructions from ----
10 // pseudo registers into register stack instructions. This pass uses live ----
11 // variable information to indicate where the FPn registers are used and their ----
12 // lifetimes. ----
13 // ----
14 // The x87 hardware tracks liveness of the stack registers, so it is necessary ----
15 // to implement exact liveness tracking between basic blocks. The CFG edges are ----
16 // partitioned into bundles where the same FP registers must be live in ----
17 // identical stack positions. Instructions are inserted at the end of each basic ----
18 // block to rearrange the live registers to match the outgoing bundle. ----
19 // ----
20 // This approach avoids splitting critical edges at the potential cost of more ----
21 // live register shuffling instructions when critical edges are present. ----
22 // ----
23 //===----------------------------------------------------------------------===// ----
24 ----

87 const TargetInstrInfo *TII = nullptr; // Machine instruction info. ----

89 // Two CFG edges are related if they leave the same block, or enter the same ----
90 // block. The transitive closure of an edge under this relation is a ----
91 // LiveBundle. It represents a set of CFG edges where the live FP stack ----
92 // registers must be allocated identically in the x87 stack. ----
93 // ----
94 // A LiveBundle is usually all the edges leaving a block, or all the edges ----
95 // entering a block, but it can contain more edges if critical edges are ----
96 // present. ----
97 // ----
98 // The set of live FP registers in a LiveBundle is calculated by bundleCFG, ----
99 // but the exact mapping of FP registers to stack slots is fixed later. ----
100 struct LiveBundle { ----
101 // Bit mask of live FP registers. Bit 0 = FP0, bit 1 = FP1, &c. ----
102 unsigned Mask = 0; ----
103 ----
104 // Number of pre-assigned live registers in FixStack. This is 0 when the ----
105 // stack order has not yet been fixed. ----
106 unsigned FixCount = 0; ----
107 ----
108 // Assigned stack order for live-in registers. ----
109 // FixStack[i] == getStackEntry(i) for all i < FixCount. ----
110 unsigned char FixStack[8]; ----
111 ----
112 LiveBundle() = default; 0
113 ----
114 // Have the live registers been assigned a stack order yet? ----
115 bool isFixed() const { return !Mask || FixCount; } 0
116 }; ----
117 ----
118 // Numbered LiveBundle structs. LiveBundles[0] is used for all CFG edges ----
119 // with no live FP registers. ----
120 SmallVector LiveBundles; ----
121 ----
122 // The edge bundle analysis provides indices into the LiveBundles vector. ----
123 EdgeBundles *Bundles = nullptr; ----
124 ----
125 // Return a bitmask of FP registers in block's live-in list. ----
126 static unsigned calcLiveInMask(MachineBasicBlock *MBB, bool RemoveFPs) { 0
127 unsigned Mask = 0; 0
128 for (MachineBasicBlock::livein_iterator I = MBB->livein_begin(); 0
129 I != MBB->livein_end(); ) { 0
130 MCPhysReg Reg = I->PhysReg; 0
131 static_assert(X86::FP6 - X86::FP0 == 6, "sequential regnums"); ----
132 if (Reg >= X86::FP0 && Reg <= X86::FP6) { 0
133 Mask |= 1 << (Reg - X86::FP0); 0
134 if (RemoveFPs) { 0
135 I = MBB->removeLiveIn(I); 0
136 continue; 0
137 } ----
138 } ----
139 ++I; 0
140 } ----
141 return Mask; 0
142 } ----

144 // Partition all the CFG edges into LiveBundles. ----
145 void bundleCFGRecomputeKillFlags(MachineFunction &MF); ----

147 MachineBasicBlock *MBB = nullptr; // Current basic block ----
148 ----
149 // The hardware keeps track of how many FP registers are live, so we have ----
150 // to model that exactly. Usually, each live register corresponds to an ----
151 // FP register, but when dealing with calls, returns, and inline ----
152 // assembly, it is sometimes necessary to have live scratch registers. ----
153 unsigned Stack[8]; // FP Registers in each stack slot... ----
154 unsigned StackTop = 0; // The current top of the FP stack. ----
155 ----
156 enum { ----
157 NumFPRegs = 8 // Including scratch pseudo-registers. ----
158 }; ----
159 ----
160 // For each live FP register, point to its Stack[] entry. ----
161 // The first entries correspond to FP0-FP6, the rest are scratch registers ----
162 // used when we need slightly different live registers than what the ----
163 // register allocator thinks. ----
164 unsigned RegMap[NumFPRegs]; ----
165 ----
166 // Set up our stack model to match the incoming registers to MBB. ----
167 void setupBlockStack(); ----
168 ----
169 // Shuffle live registers to match the expectations of successor blocks. ----
170 void finishBlockStack(); ----

172 #if !defined(NDEBUG) || defined(LLVM_ENABLE_DUMP) ----
173 void dumpStack() const { 0
174 dbgs() << "Stack contents:"; 0
175 for (unsigned i = 0; i != StackTop; ++i) { 0
176 dbgs() << " FP" << Stack[i]; 0
177 assert(RegMap[Stack[i]] == i && "Stack[] doesn't match RegMap[]!"); 0
178 } ----
179 } 0
180 #endif ----

182 /// getSlot - Return the stack slot number a particular register number is ----
183 /// in. ----
184 unsigned getSlot(unsigned RegNo) const { 0
185 assert(RegNo < NumFPRegs && "Regno out of range!"); 0
186 return RegMap[RegNo]; 0
187 } ----
188 ----
189 /// isLive - Is RegNo currently live in the stack? ----
190 bool isLive(unsigned RegNo) const { 0
191 unsigned Slot = getSlot(RegNo); 0
192 return Slot < StackTop && Stack[Slot] == RegNo; 0
193 } ----
194 ----
195 /// getStackEntry - Return the X86::FP register in register ST(i). ----
196 unsigned getStackEntry(unsigned STi) const { 0
197 if (STi >= StackTop) 0
198 report_fatal_error("Access past stack top!"); 0
199 return Stack[StackTop-1-STi]; 0
200 } ----
201 ----
202 /// getSTReg - Return the X86::ST(i) register which contains the specified ----
203 /// FP register. ----
204 unsigned getSTReg(unsigned RegNo) const { 0
205 return StackTop - 1 - getSlot(RegNo) + X86::ST0; 0
206 } ----
207 ----
208 // pushReg - Push the specified FP register onto the stack. ----
209 void pushReg(unsigned Reg) { 0
210 assert(Reg < NumFPRegs && "Register number out of range!"); 0
211 if (StackTop >= 8) 0
212 report_fatal_error("Stack overflow!"); 0
213 Stack[StackTop] = Reg; 0
214 RegMap[Reg] = StackTop++; 0
215 } 0
216 ----
217 // popReg - Pop a register from the stack. ----
218 void popReg() { 0
219 if (StackTop == 0) 0
220 report_fatal_error("Cannot pop empty stack!"); 0
221 RegMap[Stack[--StackTop]] = ~0; // Update state 0
222 } 0
223 ----
224 bool isAtTop(unsigned RegNo) const { return getSlot(RegNo) == StackTop-1; } 0
225 void moveToTop(unsigned RegNo, MachineBasicBlock::iterator I) { 0
226 DebugLoc dl = I == MBB->end() ? DebugLoc() : I->getDebugLoc(); 0
227 if (isAtTop(RegNo)) return; 0
228 ----
229 unsigned STReg = getSTReg(RegNo); 0
230 unsigned RegOnTop = getStackEntry(0); 0
231 ----
232 // Swap the slots the regs are in. ----
233 std::swap(RegMap[RegNo], RegMap[RegOnTop]); 0
234 ----
235 // Swap stack slot contents. ----
236 if (RegMap[RegOnTop] >= StackTop) 0
237 report_fatal_error("Access past stack top!"); 0
238 std::swap(Stack[RegMap[RegOnTop]], Stack[StackTop-1]); 0
239 ----
240 // Emit an fxch to update the runtime processors version of the state. ----
241 BuildMI(*MBB, I, dl, TII->get(X86::XCH_F)).addReg(STReg); 0
242 ++NumFXCH; 0
243 } 0
244 ----
245 void duplicateToTop(unsigned RegNo, unsigned AsReg, 0
246 MachineBasicBlock::iterator I) { ----
247 DebugLoc dl = I == MBB->end() ? DebugLoc() : I->getDebugLoc(); 0
248 unsigned STReg = getSTReg(RegNo); 0
249 pushReg(AsReg); // New register on top of stack 0
250 ----
251 BuildMI(*MBB, I, dl, TII->get(X86::LD_Frr)).addReg(STReg); 0
252 } 0

313 /// getFPReg - Return the X86::FPx register number for the specified operand. ----
314 /// For example, this returns 3 for X86::FP3. ----
315 static unsigned getFPReg(const MachineOperand &MO) { 0
316 assert(MO.isReg() && "Expected an FP register!"); 0
317 Register Reg = MO.getReg(); 0
318 assert(Reg >= X86::FP0 && Reg <= X86::FP6 && "Expected FP register!"); 0
319 return Reg - X86::FP0; 0
320 } ----

322 /// runOnMachineFunction - Loop over all of the basic blocks, transforming FP ----
323 /// register references into FP stack references. ----
324 /// ----
325 bool FPS::runOnMachineFunction(MachineFunction &MF) { 0
326 // We only need to run this pass if there are any FP registers used in this ----
327 // function. If it is all integer, there is nothing for us to do! ----
328 bool FPIsUsed = false; 0
329 ----
330 static_assert(X86::FP6 == X86::FP0+6, "Register enums aren't sorted right!"); ----
331 const MachineRegisterInfo &MRI = MF.getRegInfo(); 0
332 for (unsigned i = 0; i <= 6; ++i) 0
333 if (!MRI.reg_nodbg_empty(X86::FP0 + i)) { 0
334 FPIsUsed = true; 0
335 break; 0
336 } ----
337 ----
338 // Early exit. ----
339 if (!FPIsUsed) return false; 0
340 ----
341 Bundles = &getAnalysis(); 0
342 TII = MF.getSubtarget().getInstrInfo(); 0
343 ----
344 // Prepare cross-MBB liveness. ----
345 bundleCFGRecomputeKillFlags(MF); 0
346 ----
347 StackTop = 0; 0
348 ----
349 // Process the function in depth first order so that we process at least one ----
350 // of the predecessors for every reachable block in the function. ----
351 df_iterator_default_set Processed; 0
352 MachineBasicBlock *Entry = &MF.front(); 0
353 ----
354 LiveBundle &Bundle = ----
355 LiveBundles[Bundles->getBundle(Entry->getNumber(), false)]; 0
356 ----
357 // In regcall convention, some FP registers may not be passed through ----
358 // the stack, so they will need to be assigned to the stack first ----
359 if ((Entry->getParent()->getFunction().getCallingConv() == 0
360 CallingConv::X86_RegCall) && (Bundle.Mask && !Bundle.FixCount)) { 0
361 // In the register calling convention, up to one FP argument could be ----
362 // saved in the first FP register. ----
363 // If bundle.mask is non-zero and Bundle.FixCount is zero, it means ----
364 // that the FP registers contain arguments. ----
365 // The actual value is passed in FP0. ----
366 // Here we fix the stack and mark FP0 as pre-assigned register. ----
367 assert((Bundle.Mask & 0xFE) == 0 && 0
368 "Only FP0 could be passed as an argument"); ----
369 Bundle.FixCount = 1; 0
370 Bundle.FixStack[0] = 0; 0
371 } ----
372 ----
373 bool Changed = false; 0
374 for (MachineBasicBlock *BB : depth_first_ext(Entry, Processed)) 0
375 Changed |= processBasicBlock(MF, *BB); 0
376 ----
377 // Process any unreachable blocks in arbitrary order now. ----
378 if (MF.size() != Processed.size()) 0
379 for (MachineBasicBlock &BB : MF) 0
380 if (Processed.insert(&BB).second) 0
381 Changed |= processBasicBlock(MF, BB); 0
382 ----
383 LiveBundles.clear(); 0
384 ----
385 return Changed; 0
386 } 0
387 ----
388 /// bundleCFG - Scan all the basic blocks to determine consistent live-in and ----
389 /// live-out sets for the FP registers. Consistent means that the set of ----
390 /// registers live-out from a block is identical to the live-in set of all ----
391 /// successors. This is not enforced by the normal live-in lists since ----
392 /// registers may be implicitly defined, or not used by all successors. ----
393 void FPS::bundleCFGRecomputeKillFlags(MachineFunction &MF) { 0
394 assert(LiveBundles.empty() && "Stale data in LiveBundles"); 0
395 LiveBundles.resize(Bundles->getNumBundles()); 0
396 ----
397 // Gather the actual live-in masks for all MBBs. ----
398 for (MachineBasicBlock &MBB : MF) { 0
399 setKillFlags(MBB); 0
400 ----
401 const unsigned Mask = calcLiveInMask(&MBB, false); 0
402 if (!Mask) 0
403 continue; 0
404 // Update MBB ingoing bundle mask. ----
405 LiveBundles[Bundles->getBundle(MBB.getNumber(), false)].Mask |= Mask; 0
406 } ----
407 } 0

409 /// processBasicBlock - Loop over all of the instructions in the basic block, ----
410 /// transforming FP instructions into their stack form. ----
411 /// ----
412 bool FPS::processBasicBlock(MachineFunction &MF, MachineBasicBlock &BB) { 0
413 bool Changed = false; 0
414 MBB = &BB; 0
415 ----
416 setupBlockStack(); 0
417 ----
418 for (MachineBasicBlock::iterator I = BB.begin(); I != BB.end(); ++I) { 0
419 MachineInstr &MI = *I; 0
420 uint64_t Flags = MI.getDesc().TSFlags; 0
421 ----
422 unsigned FPInstClass = Flags & X86II::FPTypeMask; 0
423 if (MI.isInlineAsm()) 0
424 FPInstClass = X86II::SpecialFP; 0
425 ----
426 if (MI.isCopy() && isFPCopy(MI)) 0
427 FPInstClass = X86II::SpecialFP; 0
428 ----
429 if (MI.isImplicitDef() && 0
430 X86::RFP80RegClass.contains(MI.getOperand(0).getReg())) 0
431 FPInstClass = X86II::SpecialFP; 0
432 ----
433 if (MI.isCall()) 0
434 FPInstClass = X86II::SpecialFP; 0
435 ----
436 if (FPInstClass == X86II::NotFP) 0
437 continue; // Efficiently ignore non-fp insts! 0
438 ----
439 MachineInstr *PrevMI = nullptr; 0
440 if (I != BB.begin()) 0
441 PrevMI = &*std::prev(I); 0
442 ----
443 ++NumFP; // Keep track of # of pseudo instrs 0
444 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "\nFPInst:\t" << MI); 0
445 ----
446 // Get dead variables list now because the MI pointer may be deleted as part ----
447 // of processing! ----
448 SmallVector DeadRegs; 0
449 for (const MachineOperand &MO : MI.operands()) 0
450 if (MO.isReg() && MO.isDead()) 0
451 DeadRegs.push_back(MO.getReg()); 0
452 ----
453 switch (FPInstClass) { 0
454 case X86II::ZeroArgFP: handleZeroArgFP(I); break; 0
455 case X86II::OneArgFP: handleOneArgFP(I); break; // fstp ST(0) 0
456 case X86II::OneArgFPRW: handleOneArgFPRW(I); break; // ST(0) = fsqrt(ST(0)) 0
457 case X86II::TwoArgFP: handleTwoArgFP(I); break; 0
458 case X86II::CompareFP: handleCompareFP(I); break; 0
459 case X86II::CondMovFP: handleCondMovFP(I); break; 0
460 case X86II::SpecialFP: handleSpecialFP(I); break; 0
461 default: llvm_unreachable("Unknown FP Type!"); 0
462 } ----
463 ----
464 // Check to see if any of the values defined by this instruction are dead ----
465 // after definition. If so, pop them. ----
466 for (unsigned i = 0, e = DeadRegs.size(); i != e; ++i) { 0
467 unsigned Reg = DeadRegs[i]; 0
468 // Check if Reg is live on the stack. An inline-asm register operand that ----
469 // is in the clobber list and marked dead might not be live on the stack. ----
470 static_assert(X86::FP7 - X86::FP0 == 7, "sequential FP regnumbers"); ----
471 if (Reg >= X86::FP0 && Reg <= X86::FP6 && isLive(Reg-X86::FP0)) { 0
472 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Register FP#" << Reg - X86::FP0 << " is dead!\n"); 0
473 freeStackSlotAfter(I, Reg-X86::FP0); 0
474 } ----
475 } ----
476 ----
477 // Print out all of the instructions expanded to if -debug ----
478 LLVM_DEBUG({ 0
479 MachineBasicBlock::iterator PrevI = PrevMI; ----
480 if (I == PrevI) { ----
481 dbgs() << "Just deleted pseudo instruction\n"; ----
482 } else { ----
483 MachineBasicBlock::iterator Start = I; ----
484 // Rewind to first instruction newly inserted. ----
485 while (Start != BB.begin() && std::prev(Start) != PrevI) ----
486 --Start; ----
487 dbgs() << "Inserted instructions:\n\t"; ----
488 Start->print(dbgs()); ----
489 while (++Start != std::next(I)) { ----
490 } ----
491 } ----
492 dumpStack(); ----
493 }); ----
494 (void)PrevMI; ----
495 ----
496 Changed = true; 0
497 } 0
498 ----
499 finishBlockStack(); 0
500 ----
501 return Changed; 0
502 } ----
503 ----
504 /// setupBlockStack - Use the live bundles to set up our model of the stack ----
505 /// to match predecessors' live out stack. ----
506 void FPS::setupBlockStack() { 0
507 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "\nSetting up live-ins for " << printMBBReference(*MBB) 0
508 << " derived from " << MBB->getName() << ".\n"); ----
509 StackTop = 0; 0
510 // Get the live-in bundle for MBB. ----
511 const LiveBundle &Bundle = ----
512 LiveBundles[Bundles->getBundle(MBB->getNumber(), false)]; 0
513 ----
514 if (!Bundle.Mask) { 0
515 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Block has no FP live-ins.\n"); 0
516 return; 0
517 } ----
518 ----
519 // Depth-first iteration should ensure that we always have an assigned stack. ----
520 assert(Bundle.isFixed() && "Reached block before any predecessors"); 0
521 ----
522 // Push the fixed live-in registers. ----
523 for (unsigned i = Bundle.FixCount; i > 0; --i) { 0
524 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Live-in st(" << (i - 1) << "): %fp" 0
525 << unsigned(Bundle.FixStack[i - 1]) << '\n'); ----
526 pushReg(Bundle.FixStack[i-1]); 0
527 } ----
528 ----
529 // Kill off unwanted live-ins. This can happen with a critical edge. ----
530 // FIXME: We could keep these live registers around as zombies. They may need ----
531 // to be revived at the end of a short block. It might save a few instrs. ----
532 unsigned Mask = calcLiveInMask(MBB, /*RemoveFPs=*/true); 0
533 adjustLiveRegs(Mask, MBB->begin()); 0
534 LLVM_DEBUG(MBB->dump()); 0
535 } ----
536 ----
537 /// finishBlockStack - Revive live-outs that are implicitly defined out of ----
538 /// MBB. Shuffle live registers to match the expected fixed stack of any ----
539 /// predecessors, and ensure that all predecessors are expecting the same ----
540 /// stack. ----
541 void FPS::finishBlockStack() { 0
542 // The RET handling below takes care of return blocks for us. ----
543 if (MBB->succ_empty()) 0
544 return; 0
545 ----
546 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Setting up live-outs for " << printMBBReference(*MBB) 0
547 << " derived from " << MBB->getName() << ".\n"); ----
548 ----
549 // Get MBB's live-out bundle. ----
550 unsigned BundleIdx = Bundles->getBundle(MBB->getNumber(), true); 0
551 LiveBundle &Bundle = LiveBundles[BundleIdx]; 0
552 ----
553 // We may need to kill and define some registers to match successors. ----
554 // FIXME: This can probably be combined with the shuffle below. ----
555 MachineBasicBlock::iterator Term = MBB->getFirstTerminator(); 0
556 adjustLiveRegs(Bundle.Mask, Term); 0
557 ----
558 if (!Bundle.Mask) { 0
559 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "No live-outs.\n"); 0
560 return; 0
561 } ----
562 ----
563 // Has the stack order been fixed yet? ----
564 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "LB#" << BundleIdx << ": "); 0
565 if (Bundle.isFixed()) { 0
566 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Shuffling stack to match.\n"); 0
567 shuffleStackTop(Bundle.FixStack, Bundle.FixCount, Term); 0
568 } else { ----
569 // Not fixed yet, we get to choose. ----
570 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Fixing stack order now.\n"); 0
571 Bundle.FixCount = StackTop; 0
572 for (unsigned i = 0; i < StackTop; ++i) 0
573 Bundle.FixStack[i] = getStackEntry(i); 0
574 } ----
575 } ----

578 //===----------------------------------------------------------------------===// ----
579 // Efficient Lookup Table Support ----
580 //===----------------------------------------------------------------------===// ----
581 ----
582 namespace { ----
583 struct TableEntry { ----
584 uint16_t from; ----
585 uint16_t to; ----
586 bool operator<(const TableEntry &TE) const { return from < TE.from; } 0
587 friend bool operator<(const TableEntry &TE, unsigned V) { 0
588 return TE.from < V; 0
589 } ----
590 friend bool LLVM_ATTRIBUTE_UNUSED operator<(unsigned V, ----
591 const TableEntry &TE) { ----
592 return V < TE.from; ----
593 } ----
594 }; ----
595 } ----
596 ----
597 static int Lookup(ArrayRef Table, unsigned Opcode) { 0
598 const TableEntry *I = llvm::lower_bound(Table, Opcode); 0
599 if (I != Table.end() && I->from == Opcode) 0
600 return I->to; 0
601 return -1; 0
602 } ----
603 ----
604 #ifdef NDEBUG ----
605 #define ASSERT_SORTED(TABLE) ----
606 #else ----
607 #define ASSERT_SORTED(TABLE) \ ----
608 { \ ----
609 static std::atomic TABLE##Checked(false); \ ----
610 if (!TABLE##Checked.load(std::memory_order_relaxed)) { \ ----
611 assert(is_sorted(TABLE) && \ ----
612 "All lookup tables must be sorted for efficient access!"); \ ----
613 TABLE##Checked.store(true, std::memory_order_relaxed); \ ----
614 } \ ----
615 } ----
616 #endif ----
617 ----

791 static unsigned getConcreteOpcode(unsigned Opcode) { 0
792 ASSERT_SORTED(OpcodeTable); 0
793 int Opc = Lookup(OpcodeTable, Opcode); 0
794 assert(Opc != -1 && "FP Stack instruction not in OpcodeTable!"); 0
795 return Opc; 0
796 } ----

798 //===----------------------------------------------------------------------===// ----
799 // Helper Methods ----
800 //===----------------------------------------------------------------------===// ----
801 ----
802 // PopTable - Sorted map of instructions to their popping version. The first ----
803 // element is an instruction, the second is the version which pops. ----
804 // ----
805 static const TableEntry PopTable[] = { ----
806 { X86::ADD_FrST0 , X86::ADD_FPrST0 }, ----
807 ----
808 { X86::COMP_FST0r, X86::FCOMPP }, ----
809 { X86::COM_FIr , X86::COM_FIPr }, ----
810 { X86::COM_FST0r , X86::COMP_FST0r }, ----
811 ----
812 { X86::DIVR_FrST0, X86::DIVR_FPrST0 }, ----
813 { X86::DIV_FrST0 , X86::DIV_FPrST0 }, ----
814 ----
815 { X86::IST_F16m , X86::IST_FP16m }, ----
816 { X86::IST_F32m , X86::IST_FP32m }, ----
817 ----
818 { X86::MUL_FrST0 , X86::MUL_FPrST0 }, ----
819 ----
820 { X86::ST_F32m , X86::ST_FP32m }, ----
821 { X86::ST_F64m , X86::ST_FP64m }, ----
822 { X86::ST_Frr , X86::ST_FPrr }, ----
823 ----
824 { X86::SUBR_FrST0, X86::SUBR_FPrST0 }, ----
825 { X86::SUB_FrST0 , X86::SUB_FPrST0 }, ----
826 ----
827 { X86::UCOM_FIr , X86::UCOM_FIPr }, ----
828 ----
829 { X86::UCOM_FPr , X86::UCOM_FPPr }, ----
830 { X86::UCOM_Fr , X86::UCOM_FPr }, ----
831 }; ----
832 ----
833 static bool doesInstructionSetFPSW(MachineInstr &MI) { 0
834 if (const MachineOperand *MO = MI.findRegisterDefOperand(X86::FPSW)) 0
835 if (!MO->isDead()) 0
836 return true; 0
837 return false; 0
838 } ----
839 ----
840 static MachineBasicBlock::iterator ----
841 getNextFPInstruction(MachineBasicBlock::iterator I) { 0
842 MachineBasicBlock &MBB = *I->getParent(); 0
843 while (++I != MBB.end()) { 0
844 MachineInstr &MI = *I; 0
845 if (X86::isX87Instruction(MI)) 0
846 return I; 0
847 } ----
848 return MBB.end(); 0
849 } ----
850 ----
851 /// popStackAfter - Pop the current value off of the top of the FP stack after ----
852 /// the specified instruction. This attempts to be sneaky and combine the pop ----
853 /// into the instruction itself if possible. The iterator is left pointing to ----
854 /// the last instruction, be it a new pop instruction inserted, or the old ----
855 /// instruction if it was modified in place. ----
856 /// ----
857 void FPS::popStackAfter(MachineBasicBlock::iterator &I) { 0
858 MachineInstr &MI = *I; 0
859 const DebugLoc &dl = MI.getDebugLoc(); 0
860 ASSERT_SORTED(PopTable); 0
861 ----
862 popReg(); 0
863 ----
864 // Check to see if there is a popping version of this instruction... ----
865 int Opcode = Lookup(PopTable, I->getOpcode()); 0
866 if (Opcode != -1) { 0
867 I->setDesc(TII->get(Opcode)); 0
868 if (Opcode == X86::FCOMPP || Opcode == X86::UCOM_FPPr) 0
869 I->removeOperand(0); 0
870 MI.dropDebugNumber(); 0
871 } else { // Insert an explicit pop ----
872 // If this instruction sets FPSW, which is read in following instruction, ----
873 // insert pop after that reader. ----
874 if (doesInstructionSetFPSW(MI)) { 0
875 MachineBasicBlock &MBB = *MI.getParent(); 0
876 MachineBasicBlock::iterator Next = getNextFPInstruction(I); 0
877 if (Next != MBB.end() && Next->readsRegister(X86::FPSW)) 0
878 I = Next; 0
879 } ----
880 I = BuildMI(*MBB, ++I, dl, TII->get(X86::ST_FPrr)).addReg(X86::ST0); 0
881 } ----
882 } 0
883 ----
884 /// freeStackSlotAfter - Free the specified register from the register stack, so ----
885 /// that it is no longer in a register. If the register is currently at the top ----
886 /// of the stack, we just pop the current instruction, otherwise we store the ----
887 /// current top-of-stack into the specified slot, then pop the top of stack. ----
888 void FPS::freeStackSlotAfter(MachineBasicBlock::iterator &I, unsigned FPRegNo) { 0
889 if (getStackEntry(0) == FPRegNo) { // already at the top of stack? easy. 0
890 popStackAfter(I); 0
891 return; 0
892 } ----
893 ----
894 // Otherwise, store the top of stack into the dead slot, killing the operand ----
895 // without having to add in an explicit xchg then pop. ----
896 // ----
897 I = freeStackSlotBefore(++I, FPRegNo); 0
898 } ----
899 ----
900 /// freeStackSlotBefore - Free the specified register without trying any ----
901 /// folding. ----
902 MachineBasicBlock::iterator ----
903 FPS::freeStackSlotBefore(MachineBasicBlock::iterator I, unsigned FPRegNo) { 0
904 unsigned STReg = getSTReg(FPRegNo); 0
905 unsigned OldSlot = getSlot(FPRegNo); 0
906 unsigned TopReg = Stack[StackTop-1]; 0
907 Stack[OldSlot] = TopReg; 0
908 RegMap[TopReg] = OldSlot; 0
909 RegMap[FPRegNo] = ~0; 0
910 Stack[--StackTop] = ~0; 0
911 return BuildMI(*MBB, I, DebugLoc(), TII->get(X86::ST_FPrr)) 0
912 .addReg(STReg) 0
913 .getInstr(); 0
914 } ----
915 ----
916 /// adjustLiveRegs - Kill and revive registers such that exactly the FP ----
917 /// registers with a bit in Mask are live. ----
918 void FPS::adjustLiveRegs(unsigned Mask, MachineBasicBlock::iterator I) { 0
919 unsigned Defs = Mask; 0
920 unsigned Kills = 0; 0
921 for (unsigned i = 0; i < StackTop; ++i) { 0
922 unsigned RegNo = Stack[i]; 0
923 if (!(Defs & (1 << RegNo))) 0
924 // This register is live, but we don't want it. ----
925 Kills |= (1 << RegNo); 0
926 else ----
927 // We don't need to imp-def this live register. ----
928 Defs &= ~(1 << RegNo); 0
929 } ----
930 assert((Kills & Defs) == 0 && "Register needs killing and def'ing?"); 0
931 ----
932 // Produce implicit-defs for free by using killed registers. ----
933 while (Kills && Defs) { 0
934 unsigned KReg = llvm::countr_zero(Kills); 0
935 unsigned DReg = llvm::countr_zero(Defs); 0
936 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Renaming %fp" << KReg << " as imp %fp" << DReg 0
937 << "\n"); ----
938 std::swap(Stack[getSlot(KReg)], Stack[getSlot(DReg)]); 0
939 std::swap(RegMap[KReg], RegMap[DReg]); 0
940 Kills &= ~(1 << KReg); 0
941 Defs &= ~(1 << DReg); 0
942 } ----
943 ----
944 // Kill registers by popping. ----
945 if (Kills && I != MBB->begin()) { 0
946 MachineBasicBlock::iterator I2 = std::prev(I); 0
947 while (StackTop) { 0
948 unsigned KReg = getStackEntry(0); 0
949 if (!(Kills & (1 << KReg))) 0
950 break; 0
951 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Popping %fp" << KReg << "\n"); 0
952 popStackAfter(I2); 0
953 Kills &= ~(1 << KReg); 0
954 } ----
955 } ----
956 ----
957 // Manually kill the rest. ----
958 while (Kills) { 0
959 unsigned KReg = llvm::countr_zero(Kills); 0
960 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Killing %fp" << KReg << "\n"); 0
961 freeStackSlotBefore(I, KReg); 0
962 Kills &= ~(1 << KReg); 0
963 } ----
964 ----
965 // Load zeros for all the imp-defs. ----
966 while(Defs) { 0
967 unsigned DReg = llvm::countr_zero(Defs); 0
968 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Defining %fp" << DReg << " as 0\n"); 0
969 BuildMI(*MBB, I, DebugLoc(), TII->get(X86::LD_F0)); 0
970 pushReg(DReg); 0
971 Defs &= ~(1 << DReg); 0
972 } ----
973 ----
974 // Now we should have the correct registers live. ----
975 LLVM_DEBUG(dumpStack()); 0
976 assert(StackTop == (unsigned)llvm::popcount(Mask) && "Live count mismatch"); 0
977 } 0
978 ----
979 /// shuffleStackTop - emit fxch instructions before I to shuffle the top ----
980 /// FixCount entries into the order given by FixStack. ----
981 /// FIXME: Is there a better algorithm than insertion sort? ----
982 void FPS::shuffleStackTop(const unsigned char *FixStack, 0
983 unsigned FixCount, ----
984 MachineBasicBlock::iterator I) { ----
985 // Move items into place, starting from the desired stack bottom. ----
986 while (FixCount--) { 0
987 // Old register at position FixCount. ----
988 unsigned OldReg = getStackEntry(FixCount); 0
989 // Desired register at position FixCount. ----
990 unsigned Reg = FixStack[FixCount]; 0
991 if (Reg == OldReg) 0
992 continue; 0
993 // (Reg st0) (OldReg st0) = (Reg OldReg st0) ----
994 moveToTop(Reg, I); 0
995 if (FixCount > 0) 0
996 moveToTop(OldReg, I); 0
997 } ----
998 LLVM_DEBUG(dumpStack()); 0
999 } 0
1000 ----
1001 ----
1002 //===----------------------------------------------------------------------===// ----
1003 // Instruction transformation implementation ----
1004 //===----------------------------------------------------------------------===// ----
1005 ----
1006 void FPS::handleCall(MachineBasicBlock::iterator &I) { 0
1007 MachineInstr &MI = *I; 0
1008 unsigned STReturns = 0; 0
1009 ----
1010 bool ClobbersFPStack = false; 0
1011 for (unsigned i = 0, e = MI.getNumOperands(); i != e; ++i) { 0
1012 MachineOperand &Op = MI.getOperand(i); 0
1013 // Check if this call clobbers the FP stack. ----
1014 // is sufficient. ----
1015 if (Op.isRegMask()) { 0
1016 bool ClobbersFP0 = Op.clobbersPhysReg(X86::FP0); 0
1017 #ifndef NDEBUG ----
1018 static_assert(X86::FP7 - X86::FP0 == 7, "sequential FP regnumbers"); ----
1019 for (unsigned i = 1; i != 8; ++i) 0
1020 assert(Op.clobbersPhysReg(X86::FP0 + i) == ClobbersFP0 && 0
1021 "Inconsistent FP register clobber"); ----
1022 #endif ----
1023 ----
1024 if (ClobbersFP0) 0
1025 ClobbersFPStack = true; 0
1026 } ----
1027 ----
1028 if (!Op.isReg() || Op.getReg() < X86::FP0 || Op.getReg() > X86::FP6) 0
1029 continue; 0
1030 ----
1031 assert(Op.isImplicit() && "Expected implicit def/use"); 0
1032 ----
1033 if (Op.isDef()) 0
1034 STReturns |= 1 << getFPReg(Op); 0
1035 ----
1036 // Remove the operand so that later passes don't see it. ----
1037 MI.removeOperand(i); 0
1038 --i; 0
1039 --e; 0
1040 } ----
1041 ----
1042 // Most calls should have a regmask that clobbers the FP registers. If it ----
1043 // isn't present then the register allocator didn't spill the FP registers ----
1044 // so they are still on the stack. ----
1045 assert((ClobbersFPStack || STReturns == 0) && 0
1046 "ST returns without FP stack clobber"); ----
1047 if (!ClobbersFPStack) 0
1048 return; 0
1049 ----
1050 unsigned N = llvm::countr_one(STReturns); 0
1051 ----
1052 // FP registers used for function return must be consecutive starting at ----
1053 // FP0 ----
1054 assert(STReturns == 0 || (isMask_32(STReturns) && N <= 2)); 0
1055 ----
1056 // Reset the FP Stack - It is required because of possible leftovers from ----
1057 // passed arguments. The caller should assume that the FP stack is ----
1058 // returned empty (unless the callee returns values on FP stack). ----
1059 while (StackTop > 0) 0
1060 popReg(); 0
1061 ----
1062 for (unsigned I = 0; I < N; ++I) 0
1063 pushReg(N - I - 1); 0
1064 ----
1065 // If this call has been modified, drop all variable values defined by it. ----
1066 // We can't track them once they've been stackified. ----
1067 if (STReturns) 0
1068 I->dropDebugNumber(); 0
1069 } ----
1070 ----
1071 /// If RET has an FP register use operand, pass the first one in ST(0) and ----
1072 /// the second one in ST(1). ----
1073 void FPS::handleReturn(MachineBasicBlock::iterator &I) { 0
1074 MachineInstr &MI = *I; 0
1075 ----
1076 // Find the register operands. ----
1077 unsigned FirstFPRegOp = ~0U, SecondFPRegOp = ~0U; 0
1078 unsigned LiveMask = 0; 0
1079 ----
1080 for (unsigned i = 0, e = MI.getNumOperands(); i != e; ++i) { 0
1081 MachineOperand &Op = MI.getOperand(i); 0
1082 if (!Op.isReg() || Op.getReg() < X86::FP0 || Op.getReg() > X86::FP6) 0
1083 continue; 0
1084 // FP Register uses must be kills unless there are two uses of the same ----
1085 // register, in which case only one will be a kill. ----
1086 assert(Op.isUse() && 0
1087 (Op.isKill() || // Marked kill. ----
1088 getFPReg(Op) == FirstFPRegOp || // Second instance. ----
1089 MI.killsRegister(Op.getReg())) && // Later use is marked kill. ----
1090 "Ret only defs operands, and values aren't live beyond it"); ----
1091 ----
1092 if (FirstFPRegOp == ~0U) 0
1093 FirstFPRegOp = getFPReg(Op); 0
1094 else { ----
1095 assert(SecondFPRegOp == ~0U && "More than two fp operands!"); 0
1096 SecondFPRegOp = getFPReg(Op); 0
1097 } ----
1098 LiveMask |= (1 << getFPReg(Op)); 0
1099 ----
1100 // Remove the operand so that later passes don't see it. ----
1101 MI.removeOperand(i); 0
1102 --i; 0
1103 --e; 0
1104 } ----
1105 ----
1106 // We may have been carrying spurious live-ins, so make sure only the ----
1107 // returned registers are left live. ----
1108 adjustLiveRegs(LiveMask, MI); 0
1109 if (!LiveMask) return; // Quick check to see if any are possible. 0
1110 ----
1111 // There are only four possibilities here: ----
1112 // 1) we are returning a single FP value. In this case, it has to be in ----
1113 // ST(0) already, so just declare success by removing the value from the ----
1114 // FP Stack. ----
1115 if (SecondFPRegOp == ~0U) { 0
1116 // Assert that the top of stack contains the right FP register. ----
1117 assert(StackTop == 1 && FirstFPRegOp == getStackEntry(0) && 0
1118 "Top of stack not the right register for RET!"); ----
1119 ----
1120 // Ok, everything is good, mark the value as not being on the stack ----
1121 // anymore so that our assertion about the stack being empty at end of ----
1122 // block doesn't fire. ----
1123 StackTop = 0; 0
1124 return; 0
1125 } ----
1126 ----
1127 // Otherwise, we are returning two values: ----
1128 // 2) If returning the same value for both, we only have one thing in the FP ----
1129 // stack. Consider: RET FP1, FP1 ----
1130 if (StackTop == 1) { 0
1131 assert(FirstFPRegOp == SecondFPRegOp && FirstFPRegOp == getStackEntry(0)&& 0
1132 "Stack misconfiguration for RET!"); ----
1133 ----
1134 // Duplicate the TOS so that we return it twice. Just pick some other FPx ----
1135 // register to hold it. ----
1136 unsigned NewReg = ScratchFPReg; 0
1137 duplicateToTop(FirstFPRegOp, NewReg, MI); 0
1138 FirstFPRegOp = NewReg; 0
1139 } ----
1140 ----
1141 /// Okay we know we have two different FPx operands now: ----
1142 assert(StackTop == 2 && "Must have two values live!"); 0
1143 ----
1144 /// 3) If SecondFPRegOp is currently in ST(0) and FirstFPRegOp is currently ----
1145 /// in ST(1). In this case, emit an fxch. ----
1146 if (getStackEntry(0) == SecondFPRegOp) { 0
1147 assert(getStackEntry(1) == FirstFPRegOp && "Unknown regs live"); 0
1148 moveToTop(FirstFPRegOp, MI); 0
1149 } ----
1150 ----
1151 /// 4) Finally, FirstFPRegOp must be in ST(0) and SecondFPRegOp must be in ----
1152 /// ST(1). Just remove both from our understanding of the stack and return. ----
1153 assert(getStackEntry(0) == FirstFPRegOp && "Unknown regs live"); 0
1154 assert(getStackEntry(1) == SecondFPRegOp && "Unknown regs live"); 0
1155 StackTop = 0; 0
1156 } ----
1157 ----
1158 /// handleZeroArgFP - ST(0) = fld0 ST(0) = flds ----
1159 /// ----
1160 void FPS::handleZeroArgFP(MachineBasicBlock::iterator &I) { 0
1161 MachineInstr &MI = *I; 0
1162 unsigned DestReg = getFPReg(MI.getOperand(0)); 0
1163 ----
1164 // Change from the pseudo instruction to the concrete instruction. ----
1165 MI.removeOperand(0); // Remove the explicit ST(0) operand 0
1166 MI.setDesc(TII->get(getConcreteOpcode(MI.getOpcode()))); 0
1167 MI.addOperand( 0
1168 MachineOperand::CreateReg(X86::ST0, /*isDef*/ true, /*isImp*/ true)); 0
1169 ----
1170 // Result gets pushed on the stack. ----
1171 pushReg(DestReg); 0
1172 ----
1173 MI.dropDebugNumber(); 0
1174 } 0
1175 ----
1176 /// handleOneArgFP - fst , ST(0) ----
1177 /// ----
1178 void FPS::handleOneArgFP(MachineBasicBlock::iterator &I) { 0
1179 MachineInstr &MI = *I; 0
1180 unsigned NumOps = MI.getDesc().getNumOperands(); 0
1181 assert((NumOps == X86::AddrNumOperands + 1 || NumOps == 1) && 0
1182 "Can only handle fst* & ftst instructions!"); ----
1183 ----
1184 // Is this the last use of the source register? ----
1185 unsigned Reg = getFPReg(MI.getOperand(NumOps - 1)); 0
1186 bool KillsSrc = MI.killsRegister(X86::FP0 + Reg); 0
1187 ----
1188 // FISTP64m is strange because there isn't a non-popping versions. ----
1189 // If we have one _and_ we don't want to pop the operand, duplicate the value ----
1190 // on the stack instead of moving it. This ensure that popping the value is ----
1191 // always ok. ----
1192 // Ditto FISTTP16m, FISTTP32m, FISTTP64m, ST_FpP80m. ----
1193 // ----
1194 if (!KillsSrc && (MI.getOpcode() == X86::IST_Fp64m32 || 0
1195 MI.getOpcode() == X86::ISTT_Fp16m32 || 0
1196 MI.getOpcode() == X86::ISTT_Fp32m32 || 0
1197 MI.getOpcode() == X86::ISTT_Fp64m32 || 0
1198 MI.getOpcode() == X86::IST_Fp64m64 || 0
1199 MI.getOpcode() == X86::ISTT_Fp16m64 || 0
1200 MI.getOpcode() == X86::ISTT_Fp32m64 || 0
1201 MI.getOpcode() == X86::ISTT_Fp64m64 || 0
1202 MI.getOpcode() == X86::IST_Fp64m80 || 0
1203 MI.getOpcode() == X86::ISTT_Fp16m80 || 0
1204 MI.getOpcode() == X86::ISTT_Fp32m80 || 0
1205 MI.getOpcode() == X86::ISTT_Fp64m80 || 0
1206 MI.getOpcode() == X86::ST_FpP80m)) { 0
1207 duplicateToTop(Reg, ScratchFPReg, I); 0
1208 } else { ----
1209 moveToTop(Reg, I); // Move to the top of the stack... 0
1210 } ----
1211 ----
1212 // Convert from the pseudo instruction to the concrete instruction. ----
1213 MI.removeOperand(NumOps - 1); // Remove explicit ST(0) operand 0
1214 MI.setDesc(TII->get(getConcreteOpcode(MI.getOpcode()))); 0
1215 MI.addOperand( 0
1216 MachineOperand::CreateReg(X86::ST0, /*isDef*/ false, /*isImp*/ true)); 0
1217 ----
1218 if (MI.getOpcode() == X86::IST_FP64m || MI.getOpcode() == X86::ISTT_FP16m || 0
1219 MI.getOpcode() == X86::ISTT_FP32m || MI.getOpcode() == X86::ISTT_FP64m || 0
1220 MI.getOpcode() == X86::ST_FP80m) { 0
1221 if (StackTop == 0) 0
1222 report_fatal_error("Stack empty??"); 0
1223 --StackTop; 0
1224 } else if (KillsSrc) { // Last use of operand? 0
1225 popStackAfter(I); 0
1226 } ----
1227 ----
1228 MI.dropDebugNumber(); 0
1229 } 0
1230 ----
1231 ----
1232 /// handleOneArgFPRW: Handle instructions that read from the top of stack and ----
1233 /// replace the value with a newly computed value. These instructions may have ----
1234 /// non-fp operands after their FP operands. ----
1235 /// ----
1236 /// Examples: ----
1237 /// R1 = fchs R2 ----
1238 /// R1 = fadd R2, [mem] ----
1239 /// ----
1240 void FPS::handleOneArgFPRW(MachineBasicBlock::iterator &I) { 0
1241 MachineInstr &MI = *I; 0
1242 #ifndef NDEBUG ----
1243 unsigned NumOps = MI.getDesc().getNumOperands(); 0
1244 assert(NumOps >= 2 && "FPRW instructions must have 2 ops!!"); 0
1245 #endif ----
1246 ----
1247 // Is this the last use of the source register? ----
1248 unsigned Reg = getFPReg(MI.getOperand(1)); 0
1249 bool KillsSrc = MI.killsRegister(X86::FP0 + Reg); 0
1250 ----
1251 if (KillsSrc) { 0
1252 // If this is the last use of the source register, just make sure it's on ----
1253 // the top of the stack. ----
1254 moveToTop(Reg, I); 0
1255 if (StackTop == 0) 0
1256 report_fatal_error("Stack cannot be empty!"); 0
1257 --StackTop; 0
1258 pushReg(getFPReg(MI.getOperand(0))); 0
1259 } else { ----
1260 // If this is not the last use of the source register, _copy_ it to the top ----
1261 // of the stack. ----
1262 duplicateToTop(Reg, getFPReg(MI.getOperand(0)), I); 0
1263 } ----
1264 ----
1265 // Change from the pseudo instruction to the concrete instruction. ----
1266 MI.removeOperand(1); // Drop the source operand. 0
1267 MI.removeOperand(0); // Drop the destination operand. 0
1268 MI.setDesc(TII->get(getConcreteOpcode(MI.getOpcode()))); 0
1269 MI.dropDebugNumber(); 0
1270 } 0
1271 ----
1272 ----
1273 //===----------------------------------------------------------------------===// ----
1274 // Define tables of various ways to map pseudo instructions ----
1275 // ----
1276 ----
1277 // ForwardST0Table - Map: A = B op C into: ST(0) = ST(0) op ST(i) ----
1278 static const TableEntry ForwardST0Table[] = { ----
1279 { X86::ADD_Fp32 , X86::ADD_FST0r }, ----
1280 { X86::ADD_Fp64 , X86::ADD_FST0r }, ----
1281 { X86::ADD_Fp80 , X86::ADD_FST0r }, ----
1282 { X86::DIV_Fp32 , X86::DIV_FST0r }, ----
1283 { X86::DIV_Fp64 , X86::DIV_FST0r }, ----
1284 { X86::DIV_Fp80 , X86::DIV_FST0r }, ----
1285 { X86::MUL_Fp32 , X86::MUL_FST0r }, ----
1286 { X86::MUL_Fp64 , X86::MUL_FST0r }, ----
1287 { X86::MUL_Fp80 , X86::MUL_FST0r }, ----
1288 { X86::SUB_Fp32 , X86::SUB_FST0r }, ----
1289 { X86::SUB_Fp64 , X86::SUB_FST0r }, ----
1290 { X86::SUB_Fp80 , X86::SUB_FST0r }, ----
1291 }; ----
1292 ----
1293 // ReverseST0Table - Map: A = B op C into: ST(0) = ST(i) op ST(0) ----
1294 static const TableEntry ReverseST0Table[] = { ----
1295 { X86::ADD_Fp32 , X86::ADD_FST0r }, // commutative ----
1296 { X86::ADD_Fp64 , X86::ADD_FST0r }, // commutative ----
1297 { X86::ADD_Fp80 , X86::ADD_FST0r }, // commutative ----
1298 { X86::DIV_Fp32 , X86::DIVR_FST0r }, ----
1299 { X86::DIV_Fp64 , X86::DIVR_FST0r }, ----
1300 { X86::DIV_Fp80 , X86::DIVR_FST0r }, ----
1301 { X86::MUL_Fp32 , X86::MUL_FST0r }, // commutative ----
1302 { X86::MUL_Fp64 , X86::MUL_FST0r }, // commutative ----
1303 { X86::MUL_Fp80 , X86::MUL_FST0r }, // commutative ----
1304 { X86::SUB_Fp32 , X86::SUBR_FST0r }, ----
1305 { X86::SUB_Fp64 , X86::SUBR_FST0r }, ----
1306 { X86::SUB_Fp80 , X86::SUBR_FST0r }, ----
1307 }; ----
1308 ----
1309 // ForwardSTiTable - Map: A = B op C into: ST(i) = ST(0) op ST(i) ----
1310 static const TableEntry ForwardSTiTable[] = { ----
1311 { X86::ADD_Fp32 , X86::ADD_FrST0 }, // commutative ----
1312 { X86::ADD_Fp64 , X86::ADD_FrST0 }, // commutative ----
1313 { X86::ADD_Fp80 , X86::ADD_FrST0 }, // commutative ----
1314 { X86::DIV_Fp32 , X86::DIVR_FrST0 }, ----
1315 { X86::DIV_Fp64 , X86::DIVR_FrST0 }, ----
1316 { X86::DIV_Fp80 , X86::DIVR_FrST0 }, ----
1317 { X86::MUL_Fp32 , X86::MUL_FrST0 }, // commutative ----
1318 { X86::MUL_Fp64 , X86::MUL_FrST0 }, // commutative ----
1319 { X86::MUL_Fp80 , X86::MUL_FrST0 }, // commutative ----
1320 { X86::SUB_Fp32 , X86::SUBR_FrST0 }, ----
1321 { X86::SUB_Fp64 , X86::SUBR_FrST0 }, ----
1322 { X86::SUB_Fp80 , X86::SUBR_FrST0 }, ----
1323 }; ----
1324 ----
1325 // ReverseSTiTable - Map: A = B op C into: ST(i) = ST(i) op ST(0) ----
1326 static const TableEntry ReverseSTiTable[] = { ----
1327 { X86::ADD_Fp32 , X86::ADD_FrST0 }, ----
1328 { X86::ADD_Fp64 , X86::ADD_FrST0 }, ----
1329 { X86::ADD_Fp80 , X86::ADD_FrST0 }, ----
1330 { X86::DIV_Fp32 , X86::DIV_FrST0 }, ----
1331 { X86::DIV_Fp64 , X86::DIV_FrST0 }, ----
1332 { X86::DIV_Fp80 , X86::DIV_FrST0 }, ----
1333 { X86::MUL_Fp32 , X86::MUL_FrST0 }, ----
1334 { X86::MUL_Fp64 , X86::MUL_FrST0 }, ----
1335 { X86::MUL_Fp80 , X86::MUL_FrST0 }, ----
1336 { X86::SUB_Fp32 , X86::SUB_FrST0 }, ----
1337 { X86::SUB_Fp64 , X86::SUB_FrST0 }, ----
1338 { X86::SUB_Fp80 , X86::SUB_FrST0 }, ----
1339 }; ----
1340 ----
1341 ----
1342 /// handleTwoArgFP - Handle instructions like FADD and friends which are virtual ----
1343 /// instructions which need to be simplified and possibly transformed. ----
1344 /// ----
1345 /// Result: ST(0) = fsub ST(0), ST(i) ----
1346 /// ST(i) = fsub ST(0), ST(i) ----
1347 /// ST(0) = fsubr ST(0), ST(i) ----
1348 /// ST(i) = fsubr ST(0), ST(i) ----
1349 /// ----
1350 void FPS::handleTwoArgFP(MachineBasicBlock::iterator &I) { 0
1351 ASSERT_SORTED(ForwardST0Table); ASSERT_SORTED(ReverseST0Table); 0
1352 ASSERT_SORTED(ForwardSTiTable); ASSERT_SORTED(ReverseSTiTable); 0
1353 MachineInstr &MI = *I; 0
1354 ----
1355 unsigned NumOperands = MI.getDesc().getNumOperands(); 0
1356 assert(NumOperands == 3 && "Illegal TwoArgFP instruction!"); 0
1357 unsigned Dest = getFPReg(MI.getOperand(0)); 0
1358 unsigned Op0 = getFPReg(MI.getOperand(NumOperands - 2)); 0
1359 unsigned Op1 = getFPReg(MI.getOperand(NumOperands - 1)); 0
1360 bool KillsOp0 = MI.killsRegister(X86::FP0 + Op0); 0
1361 bool KillsOp1 = MI.killsRegister(X86::FP0 + Op1); 0
1362 const DebugLoc &dl = MI.getDebugLoc(); 0
1363 ----
1364 unsigned TOS = getStackEntry(0); 0
1365 ----
1366 // One of our operands must be on the top of the stack. If neither is yet, we ----
1367 // need to move one. ----
1368 if (Op0 != TOS && Op1 != TOS) { // No operand at TOS? 0
1369 // We can choose to move either operand to the top of the stack. If one of ----
1370 // the operands is killed by this instruction, we want that one so that we ----
1371 // can update right on top of the old version. ----
1372 if (KillsOp0) { 0
1373 moveToTop(Op0, I); // Move dead operand to TOS. 0
1374 TOS = Op0; 0
1375 } else if (KillsOp1) { 0
1376 moveToTop(Op1, I); 0
1377 TOS = Op1; 0
1378 } else { ----
1379 // All of the operands are live after this instruction executes, so we ----
1380 // cannot update on top of any operand. Because of this, we must ----
1381 // duplicate one of the stack elements to the top. It doesn't matter ----
1382 // which one we pick. ----
1383 // ----
1384 duplicateToTop(Op0, Dest, I); 0
1385 Op0 = TOS = Dest; 0
1386 KillsOp0 = true; 0
1387 } ----
1388 } else if (!KillsOp0 && !KillsOp1) { 0
1389 // If we DO have one of our operands at the top of the stack, but we don't ----
1390 // have a dead operand, we must duplicate one of the operands to a new slot ----
1391 // on the stack. ----
1392 duplicateToTop(Op0, Dest, I); 0
1393 Op0 = TOS = Dest; 0
1394 KillsOp0 = true; 0
1395 } ----
1396 ----
1397 // Now we know that one of our operands is on the top of the stack, and at ----
1398 // least one of our operands is killed by this instruction. ----
1399 assert((TOS == Op0 || TOS == Op1) && (KillsOp0 || KillsOp1) && 0
1400 "Stack conditions not set up right!"); ----
1401 ----
1402 // We decide which form to use based on what is on the top of the stack, and ----
1403 // which operand is killed by this instruction. ----
1404 ArrayRef InstTable; 0
1405 bool isForward = TOS == Op0; 0
1406 bool updateST0 = (TOS == Op0 && !KillsOp1) || (TOS == Op1 && !KillsOp0); 0
1407 if (updateST0) { 0
1408 if (isForward) 0
1409 InstTable = ForwardST0Table; 0
1410 else ----
1411 InstTable = ReverseST0Table; 0
1412 } else { ----
1413 if (isForward) 0
1414 InstTable = ForwardSTiTable; 0
1415 else ----
1416 InstTable = ReverseSTiTable; 0
1417 } ----
1418 ----
1419 int Opcode = Lookup(InstTable, MI.getOpcode()); 0
1420 assert(Opcode != -1 && "Unknown TwoArgFP pseudo instruction!"); 0
1421 ----
1422 // NotTOS - The register which is not on the top of stack... ----
1423 unsigned NotTOS = (TOS == Op0) ? Op1 : Op0; 0
1424 ----
1425 // Replace the old instruction with a new instruction ----
1426 MBB->remove(&*I++); 0
1427 I = BuildMI(*MBB, I, dl, TII->get(Opcode)).addReg(getSTReg(NotTOS)); 0
1428 ----
1429 if (!MI.mayRaiseFPException()) 0
1430 I->setFlag(MachineInstr::MIFlag::NoFPExcept); 0
1431 ----
1432 // If both operands are killed, pop one off of the stack in addition to ----
1433 // overwriting the other one. ----
1434 if (KillsOp0 && KillsOp1 && Op0 != Op1) { 0
1435 assert(!updateST0 && "Should have updated other operand!"); 0
1436 popStackAfter(I); // Pop the top of stack 0
1437 } ----
1438 ----
1439 // Update stack information so that we know the destination register is now on ----
1440 // the stack. ----
1441 unsigned UpdatedSlot = getSlot(updateST0 ? TOS : NotTOS); 0
1442 assert(UpdatedSlot < StackTop && Dest < 7); 0
1443 Stack[UpdatedSlot] = Dest; 0
1444 RegMap[Dest] = UpdatedSlot; 0
1445 MBB->getParent()->deleteMachineInstr(&MI); // Remove the old instruction 0
1446 } 0
1447 ----
1448 /// handleCompareFP - Handle FUCOM and FUCOMI instructions, which have two FP ----
1449 /// register arguments and no explicit destinations. ----
1450 /// ----
1451 void FPS::handleCompareFP(MachineBasicBlock::iterator &I) { 0
1452 MachineInstr &MI = *I; 0
1453 ----
1454 unsigned NumOperands = MI.getDesc().getNumOperands(); 0
1455 assert(NumOperands == 2 && "Illegal FUCOM* instruction!"); 0
1456 unsigned Op0 = getFPReg(MI.getOperand(NumOperands - 2)); 0
1457 unsigned Op1 = getFPReg(MI.getOperand(NumOperands - 1)); 0
1458 bool KillsOp0 = MI.killsRegister(X86::FP0 + Op0); 0
1459 bool KillsOp1 = MI.killsRegister(X86::FP0 + Op1); 0
1460 ----
1461 // Make sure the first operand is on the top of stack, the other one can be ----
1462 // anywhere. ----
1463 moveToTop(Op0, I); 0
1464 ----
1465 // Change from the pseudo instruction to the concrete instruction. ----
1466 MI.getOperand(0).setReg(getSTReg(Op1)); 0
1467 MI.removeOperand(1); 0
1468 MI.setDesc(TII->get(getConcreteOpcode(MI.getOpcode()))); 0
1469 MI.dropDebugNumber(); 0
1470 ----
1471 // If any of the operands are killed by this instruction, free them. ----
1472 if (KillsOp0) freeStackSlotAfter(I, Op0); 0
1473 if (KillsOp1 && Op0 != Op1) freeStackSlotAfter(I, Op1); 0
1474 } 0
1475 ----
1476 /// handleCondMovFP - Handle two address conditional move instructions. These ----
1477 /// instructions move a st(i) register to st(0) iff a condition is true. These ----
1478 /// instructions require that the first operand is at the top of the stack, but ----
1479 /// otherwise don't modify the stack at all. ----
1480 void FPS::handleCondMovFP(MachineBasicBlock::iterator &I) { 0
1481 MachineInstr &MI = *I; 0
1482 ----
1483 unsigned Op0 = getFPReg(MI.getOperand(0)); 0
1484 unsigned Op1 = getFPReg(MI.getOperand(2)); 0
1485 bool KillsOp1 = MI.killsRegister(X86::FP0 + Op1); 0
1486 ----
1487 // The first operand *must* be on the top of the stack. ----
1488 moveToTop(Op0, I); 0
1489 ----
1490 // Change the second operand to the stack register that the operand is in. ----
1491 // Change from the pseudo instruction to the concrete instruction. ----
1492 MI.removeOperand(0); 0
1493 MI.removeOperand(1); 0
1494 MI.getOperand(0).setReg(getSTReg(Op1)); 0
1495 MI.setDesc(TII->get(getConcreteOpcode(MI.getOpcode()))); 0
1496 MI.dropDebugNumber(); 0
1497 ----
1498 // If we kill the second operand, make sure to pop it from the stack. ----
1499 if (Op0 != Op1 && KillsOp1) { 0
1500 // Get this value off of the register stack. ----
1501 freeStackSlotAfter(I, Op1); 0
1502 } ----
1503 } 0
1504 ----
1505 ----
1506 /// handleSpecialFP - Handle special instructions which behave unlike other ----
1507 /// floating point instructions. This is primarily intended for use by pseudo ----
1508 /// instructions. ----
1509 /// ----
1510 void FPS::handleSpecialFP(MachineBasicBlock::iterator &Inst) { 0
1511 MachineInstr &MI = *Inst; 0
1512 ----
1513 if (MI.isCall()) { 0
1514 handleCall(Inst); 0
1515 return; 0
1516 } ----
1517 ----
1518 if (MI.isReturn()) { 0
1519 handleReturn(Inst); 0
1520 return; 0
1521 } ----
1522 ----
1523 switch (MI.getOpcode()) { 0
1524 default: llvm_unreachable("Unknown SpecialFP instruction!"); 0
1525 case TargetOpcode::COPY: { 0
1526 // We handle three kinds of copies: FP <- FP, FP <- ST, and ST <- FP. ----
1527 const MachineOperand &MO1 = MI.getOperand(1); 0
1528 const MachineOperand &MO0 = MI.getOperand(0); 0
1529 bool KillsSrc = MI.killsRegister(MO1.getReg()); 0
1530 ----
1531 // FP <- FP copy. ----
1532 unsigned DstFP = getFPReg(MO0); 0
1533 unsigned SrcFP = getFPReg(MO1); 0
1534 assert(isLive(SrcFP) && "Cannot copy dead register"); 0
1535 if (KillsSrc) { 0
1536 // If the input operand is killed, we can just change the owner of the ----
1537 // incoming stack slot into the result. ----
1538 unsigned Slot = getSlot(SrcFP); 0
1539 Stack[Slot] = DstFP; 0
1540 RegMap[DstFP] = Slot; 0
1541 } else { ----
1542 // For COPY we just duplicate the specified value to a new stack slot. ----
1543 // This could be made better, but would require substantial changes. ----
1544 duplicateToTop(SrcFP, DstFP, Inst); 0
1545 } ----
1546 break; 0
1547 } ----
1548 ----
1549 case TargetOpcode::IMPLICIT_DEF: { 0
1550 // All FP registers must be explicitly defined, so load a 0 instead. ----
1551 unsigned Reg = MI.getOperand(0).getReg() - X86::FP0; 0
1552 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Emitting LD_F0 for implicit FP" << Reg << '\n'); 0
1553 BuildMI(*MBB, Inst, MI.getDebugLoc(), TII->get(X86::LD_F0)); 0
1554 pushReg(Reg); 0
1555 break; 0
1556 } ----
1557 ----
1558 case TargetOpcode::INLINEASM: 0
1559 case TargetOpcode::INLINEASM_BR: { ----
1560 // The inline asm MachineInstr currently only *uses* FP registers for the ----
1561 // 'f' constraint. These should be turned into the current ST(x) register ----
1562 // in the machine instr. ----
1563 // ----
1564 // There are special rules for x87 inline assembly. The compiler must know ----
1565 // exactly how many registers are popped and pushed implicitly by the asm. ----
1566 // Otherwise it is not possible to restore the stack state after the inline ----
1567 // asm. ----
1568 // ----
1569 // There are 3 kinds of input operands: ----
1570 // ----
1571 // 1. Popped inputs. These must appear at the stack top in ST0-STn. A ----
1572 // popped input operand must be in a fixed stack slot, and it is either ----
1573 // tied to an output operand, or in the clobber list. The MI has ST use ----
1574 // and def operands for these inputs. ----
1575 // ----
1576 // 2. Fixed inputs. These inputs appear in fixed stack slots, but are ----
1577 // preserved by the inline asm. The fixed stack slots must be STn-STm ----
1578 // following the popped inputs. A fixed input operand cannot be tied to ----
1579 // an output or appear in the clobber list. The MI has ST use operands ----
1580 // and no defs for these inputs. ----
1581 // ----
1582 // 3. Preserved inputs. These inputs use the "f" constraint which is ----
1583 // represented as an FP register. The inline asm won't change these ----
1584 // stack slots. ----
1585 // ----
1586 // Outputs must be in ST registers, FP outputs are not allowed. Clobbered ----
1587 // registers do not count as output operands. The inline asm changes the ----
1588 // stack as if it popped all the popped inputs and then pushed all the ----
1589 // output operands. ----
1590 ----
1591 // Scan the assembly for ST registers used, defined and clobbered. We can ----
1592 // only tell clobbers from defs by looking at the asm descriptor. ----
1593 unsigned STUses = 0, STDefs = 0, STClobbers = 0; 0
1594 unsigned NumOps = 0; 0
1595 SmallSet FRegIdx; 0
1596 unsigned RCID; ----
1597 ----
1598 for (unsigned i = InlineAsm::MIOp_FirstOperand, e = MI.getNumOperands(); 0
1599 i != e && MI.getOperand(i).isImm(); i += 1 + NumOps) { 0
1600 unsigned Flags = MI.getOperand(i).getImm(); 0
1601 ----
1602 NumOps = InlineAsm::getNumOperandRegisters(Flags); 0
1603 if (NumOps != 1) 0
1604 continue; 0
1605 const MachineOperand &MO = MI.getOperand(i + 1); 0
1606 if (!MO.isReg()) 0
1607 continue; 0
1608 unsigned STReg = MO.getReg() - X86::FP0; 0
1609 if (STReg >= 8) 0
1610 continue; 0
1611 ----
1612 // If the flag has a register class constraint, this must be an operand ----
1613 // with constraint "f". Record its index and continue. ----
1614 if (InlineAsm::hasRegClassConstraint(Flags, RCID)) { 0
1615 FRegIdx.insert(i + 1); 0
1616 continue; 0
1617 } ----
1618 ----
1619 switch (InlineAsm::getKind(Flags)) { 0
1620 case InlineAsm::Kind_RegUse: 0
1621 STUses |= (1u << STReg); 0
1622 break; 0
1623 case InlineAsm::Kind_RegDef: 0
1624 case InlineAsm::Kind_RegDefEarlyClobber: ----
1625 STDefs |= (1u << STReg); 0
1626 break; 0
1627 case InlineAsm::Kind_Clobber: 0
1628 STClobbers |= (1u << STReg); 0
1629 break; 0
1630 default: 0
1631 break; 0
1632 } ----
1633 } ----
1634 ----
1635 if (STUses && !isMask_32(STUses)) 0
1636 MI.emitError("fixed input regs must be last on the x87 stack"); 0
1637 unsigned NumSTUses = llvm::countr_one(STUses); 0
1638 ----
1639 // Defs must be contiguous from the stack top. ST0-STn. ----

1643 } ----

1648 MI.emitError("clobbers must be last on the x87 stack"); 0
1649 ----
1650 // Popped inputs are the ones that are also clobbered or defined. ----
1651 unsigned STPopped = STUses & (STDefs | STClobbers); 0
1652 if (STPopped && !isMask_32(STPopped)) 0
1653 MI.emitError("implicitly popped regs must be last on the x87 stack"); 0
1654 unsigned NumSTPopped = llvm::countr_one(STPopped); 0
1655 ----
1656 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Asm uses " << NumSTUses << " fixed regs, pops " 0
1657 << NumSTPopped << ", and defines " << NumSTDefs ----
1658 << " regs.\n"); ----
1659 ----
1660 #ifndef NDEBUG ----
1661 // If any input operand uses constraint "f", all output register ----
1662 // constraints must be early-clobber defs. ----
1663 for (unsigned I = 0, E = MI.getNumOperands(); I < E; ++I) 0

1667 } ----
1668 #endif ----
1669 ----
1670 // Collect all FP registers (register operands with constraints "t", "u", ----
1671 // and "f") to kill afer the instruction. ----
1672 unsigned FPKills = ((1u << NumFPRegs) - 1) & ~0xff; 0

1675 continue; 0

1679 // asm. We just remember it for now, and pop them all off at the end in ----
1680 // a batch. ----
1681 if (Op.isUse() && Op.isKill()) 0

1683 } ----
1684 ----

1686 FPKills &= ~(STDefs | STClobbers); 0
1687 ----
1688 // Now we can rearrange the live registers to match what was requested. ----
1689 unsigned char STUsesArray[8]; ----

1715 ----
1716 // Simulate the inline asm popping its inputs and pushing its outputs. ----
